WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.440
Hello, I'm Mina Çetinkaya-Rundel. I'm a data scientist and professional educator at RStudio,

00:00:11.440 --> 00:00:16.240
as well as faculty at the University of Edinburgh and Duke University. If you're also an educator

00:00:16.240 --> 00:00:20.559
teaching data science, you might find yourself in the following scenario, particularly this

00:00:20.559 --> 00:00:21.559
year.

00:00:21.559 --> 00:00:26.000
Your department chair says, your data science course is going spectacularly. We'd love to

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:32.639
expand it, and you say a big, yay. But then they say, oh, and you're going to need to

00:00:32.639 --> 00:00:41.320
do it all online, and you say, yay? And they follow up with, and we can't provide any additional

00:00:41.320 --> 00:00:46.439
support, you get the same number of TAs as before. And you start thinking to yourself,

00:00:46.439 --> 00:00:50.639
am I supposed to say yay?

00:00:50.639 --> 00:00:54.759
As enrolments in statistics and data science courses grow, and as these courses become

00:00:54.759 --> 00:00:59.799
more and more computational, educators are faced with an interesting challenge, providing

00:00:59.799 --> 00:01:05.279
timely and meaningful feedback, particularly with online delivery of courses. I'm sure

00:01:05.279 --> 00:01:11.120
we all agree that feedback should be meaningful, but traditionally, meaningful, helpful, constructive

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:17.080
feedback requires human effort and can take a significant amount of time for large courses,

00:01:17.080 --> 00:01:22.160
especially if they're under-resourced, which, let's face it, they tend to be. Timeliness

00:01:22.160 --> 00:01:28.320
of feedback is just as important as meaningfulness. The longer time passes between when a student

00:01:28.320 --> 00:01:34.599
turns in an assignment and when they get feedback on it, the lower the utility of that feedback.

00:01:34.599 --> 00:01:40.279
For certain assignments, like an open-ended project, this trade-off is absolutely reasonable,

00:01:40.279 --> 00:01:45.360
because it's really difficult, if not impossible, to replace human feedback with something else

00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:49.959
in such an assignment. But for others, there are alternatives.

00:01:49.959 --> 00:01:54.360
One such option is a Learn R tutorial, and if you've ever used Learn R before, the tutorial

00:01:54.360 --> 00:01:58.120
probably looked a little bit different than this, and that is just to say that with a

00:01:58.120 --> 00:02:01.959
little bit of CSS and theming, you can make your Learn R tutorials look like whatever

00:02:01.959 --> 00:02:06.639
you like. I like starting my Learn R tutorials with a bit of narrative, usually a little

00:02:06.639 --> 00:02:11.460
bit longer than this about the data and the analysis we're going to work through and introduce

00:02:11.460 --> 00:02:16.199
the students to the packages, and I like using the progressive reveal option, so they have

00:02:16.279 --> 00:02:21.559
to deliberately click through the material. I also like providing some ready-to-run code

00:02:21.559 --> 00:02:25.759
at the beginning, so they don't need to start working on exercises right away, but they

00:02:25.759 --> 00:02:30.800
do need to start interacting with the document. Here they're working on a dataset on Airbnb

00:02:30.800 --> 00:02:34.759
listings in Edinburgh, and the first thing we're asking them to do is to take a look

00:02:34.759 --> 00:02:40.240
at the variable names. It is not necessarily meaningful interactivity, but maybe it introduces

00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:45.679
them a little bit to the structure of a Learn R tutorial and how to interact with it, and

00:02:45.679 --> 00:02:50.160
potentially also helps build a little bit of anticipation around what the result is

00:02:50.160 --> 00:02:54.600
going to look like when they hit run code, as opposed to providing them with a static

00:02:54.600 --> 00:03:00.080
document where the code output is already provided. But really where Learn R tutorial

00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:05.800
shines are these coding exercises, where the students can try out some code, submit their

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:10.960
answer, and you can provide custom feedback to them. So the first exercise here says how

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:16.399
many Airbnb listings are included in this dataset. Let's imagine the student decided

00:03:16.399 --> 00:03:21.360
to look at the number of columns as opposed to the number of rows. The feedback that they're

00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:26.000
going to get sounds just like the type of thing I would say to them if I was working

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:30.520
through the exercises with them and trying to nudge them in the right direction. It says,

00:03:30.520 --> 00:03:35.839
did you calculate the number of columns instead of number of rows? So you can write these

00:03:35.839 --> 00:03:43.039
very precise feedback based on your anticipation about the types of mistakes students can make.

00:03:43.039 --> 00:03:47.479
And obviously, it's not possible to anticipate all possible mistakes. So what if a student

00:03:47.479 --> 00:03:53.039
chooses to try out some code that I didn't anticipate they might try out? For that, I

00:03:53.039 --> 00:03:57.759
like providing some canned feedback that's still constructive and still nudges them in

00:03:57.759 --> 00:04:02.440
the right direction. It says something like, each observation is represented in one row.

00:04:02.440 --> 00:04:08.000
Can you remember which function we used to calculate the number of rows? And finally,

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.880
let's get this question correct. I'm going to use the nrow function to do that. Let's

00:04:12.880 --> 00:04:17.320
run our code and submit our answer. You'll see that we've got the green banner, which

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:21.760
is great, but it doesn't just say correct, well done. It says a little bit more. So I

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:28.839
like using the space for the message for the correct answers to give them a little bit

00:04:28.880 --> 00:04:35.880
more information about what's to come next. So I also like following on my coding exercises

00:04:38.119 --> 00:04:44.559
with some multiple choice exercises, something that allows the students to take the code

00:04:44.559 --> 00:04:49.320
output that they saw and put it in the context of the data set that they're working with,

00:04:49.320 --> 00:04:54.160
which is so important for teaching statistics and data science. So what does each row in

00:04:54.320 --> 00:04:59.519
the eddybnb data set represent? That's an individual Airbnb listing. And again, we can

00:04:59.519 --> 00:05:05.200
use the feedback to give them a little bit more information or something to think about.

00:05:05.200 --> 00:05:10.260
If you would like to see the code for this Learn R tutorial, both in terms of creating

00:05:10.260 --> 00:05:15.279
the exercises and also the theme and the look, you can test drive it on RStudio Cloud or

00:05:15.279 --> 00:05:18.959
you can view the code on GitHub. And I'll be providing links to all of this at the end

00:05:18.959 --> 00:05:24.359
of the talk. For now, I'd like to talk a little bit about writing effective exercises.

00:05:24.359 --> 00:05:28.820
So let's start with an exercise in mind. The three most expensive neighborhoods in terms

00:05:28.820 --> 00:05:33.600
of mean nightly price are Newtown, Old Town, and West End. Calculate the median number

00:05:33.600 --> 00:05:39.600
of reviews in these neighborhoods and arrange them in descending order. One option would

00:05:39.600 --> 00:05:45.239
be to provide no scaffolding whatsoever, so an entirely empty canvas for students to work

00:05:45.239 --> 00:05:50.519
with. And the thing about this is we've really not given them any direction in terms of how

00:05:50.519 --> 00:05:55.320
to get started. And instead, what we've given them is this giant button that says solution.

00:05:55.320 --> 00:05:59.839
And it's so tempting to simply go, all right, let me take a look at the solution, copy it

00:05:59.839 --> 00:06:06.359
to my clipboard, paste it, run my code, and submit my answer. And lovely job, I got it

00:06:06.359 --> 00:06:11.239
right. But did I learn anything from this experience? Not really. This is not to say

00:06:11.239 --> 00:06:15.239
your students are all going to peek into the solution code. But I think one thing to

00:06:15.239 --> 00:06:20.959
keep in mind about providing no scaffolding whatsoever is that I think there are better

00:06:20.959 --> 00:06:26.679
venues for giving such exercises. So for assignments where the students already have to work in

00:06:26.679 --> 00:06:32.880
the RStudio IDE, either in an R Markdown document or in an R script, I think is a better venue

00:06:32.880 --> 00:06:38.720
for a more open-ended question where you provide no scaffolding whatsoever.

00:06:38.720 --> 00:06:44.000
Here we've given them no scaffolding, and we've also done something else where we've

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:51.440
basically are doing this strict code-checking business. So let's say that your student,

00:06:51.440 --> 00:06:57.920
with no scaffolding provided to them, actually decided to move the filter over here. They

00:06:57.920 --> 00:07:02.720
group by and summarize first, and then they filter. And if they run their code, they're

00:07:02.720 --> 00:07:08.359
going to get the exact same response, but their code is not marked as correct. Because

00:07:08.399 --> 00:07:14.040
with the grade this code function, what is happening under the hood is that the grade

00:07:14.040 --> 00:07:19.600
this package is checking the code your student wrote and the solution code you provided and

00:07:19.600 --> 00:07:25.160
looks for a one-to-one match. So it says that I expected you to call summarize where you

00:07:25.160 --> 00:07:31.040
called filter, give it another try. Sure, you might say that no, this is exactly how

00:07:31.040 --> 00:07:35.880
I want my students to do things, but I think that's not really entirely fair, especially

00:07:35.880 --> 00:07:41.959
because they actually got the right answer. So the strict code-checking with no scaffolding

00:07:41.959 --> 00:07:48.440
whatsoever can lead to situations where students get the right answer but are not necessarily

00:07:48.440 --> 00:07:55.320
marked correct, if you will. Another option would be to provide a little bit of scaffolding,

00:07:55.320 --> 00:08:00.299
but here we're still doing the strict check. So here we've given them a really nice structure

00:08:00.299 --> 00:08:05.519
for how to write their code, and obviously we've made the exercise a lot easier for them,

00:08:05.519 --> 00:08:10.660
but that might be okay if this is one of the first few times they're seeing these multi-line

00:08:10.660 --> 00:08:18.359
dplyr chains. So these Learn R tutorials are a great place to provide additional opportunities

00:08:18.359 --> 00:08:25.000
for kind of drill-type exercises students can work through at the beginning when they

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:31.079
are first introduced to a new topic. And you can also provide hints for them. So with these

00:08:31.320 --> 00:08:37.159
hints, let's take a look at that. I like writing them in a progressive way where they can scroll

00:08:37.159 --> 00:08:42.919
through and get a chance to potentially think about what their answer should look like at

00:08:42.919 --> 00:08:48.280
each stage. And sure, they could at the end see the solution if you want them to, but at least

00:08:48.280 --> 00:08:53.479
it makes them think along the way as well. So let's go ahead and run this code and submit the

00:08:53.479 --> 00:08:59.559
answer. I think in this structure there is no worry that they would be putting their filter

00:08:59.559 --> 00:09:05.000
function later on because we had already provided the scaffolding. However, since we're doing a

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:12.359
strict check, what if the student in the last line forgot to actually put things in descending order?

00:09:12.359 --> 00:09:18.039
So let's go ahead and run that code, and obviously this is not the correct answer, but the feedback

00:09:18.039 --> 00:09:23.719
that we get tends to be not very informative when we use the grade this code function here.

00:09:23.719 --> 00:09:30.119
So it's basically saying, I expected you to call desk for descending where you wrote median rating.

00:09:30.119 --> 00:09:36.280
And in fact, here on line five, that statement is correct. But does it actually sound like the type

00:09:36.280 --> 00:09:40.599
of thing you would say to your student if you are standing right behind them and trying to

00:09:40.599 --> 00:09:46.039
nudge them in the right direction? Not really. It doesn't seem like very human-friendly feedback.

00:09:46.039 --> 00:09:52.200
So my recommendation overall would be to provide some scaffolding and also provide some flexibility.

00:09:52.200 --> 00:09:58.440
This is another approach to scaffolding where perhaps if this tutorial is coming later on, if

00:09:58.440 --> 00:10:03.320
they've already done a bunch with dplyr and you don't want to give them that whole structure,

00:10:03.320 --> 00:10:08.599
you might at least give them a little bit of scaffolding to say, hey, I want you to use a dplyr

00:10:08.599 --> 00:10:16.200
pipeline for answering this question. And let's go ahead and give that a try. So here I am going to

00:10:17.159 --> 00:10:22.760
forget to put things in descending order and run my code. And let's take a look at the feedback that

00:10:22.760 --> 00:10:28.520
I get. I actually am getting human-friendly feedback here. You've successfully calculated

00:10:28.520 --> 00:10:33.400
the median number of ratings, but did you forget to arrange them in descending order?

00:10:33.400 --> 00:10:39.559
How did I do this? Here, instead of checking their code, we're actually checking their results.

00:10:39.559 --> 00:10:45.799
And one nice thing about doing that is, so let's go back and put the right answer here. What if

00:10:45.799 --> 00:10:52.359
they made that one change where they were doing group by and summarize and then filter to have

00:10:52.359 --> 00:10:57.559
them run the code and submit their answer? And in fact, this time it is marked as correct because

00:10:57.559 --> 00:11:02.599
again, we're checking the results and not the code. So what does this look like under the hood?

00:11:02.599 --> 00:11:08.599
It's a bit more to write the code checking if you're using the grade this function,

00:11:09.320 --> 00:11:15.000
because you actually need to think about what are the various answers they might get and actually

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:21.159
write some passive or fail if type statements. So here I have one passive statement that says

00:11:21.159 --> 00:11:26.599
if their result is this table in this particular order, we're going to say, yep, you did the right

00:11:26.599 --> 00:11:33.080
thing. But if they have put them in ascending order, then we're going to give them a specific

00:11:33.080 --> 00:11:37.719
message for that. Or if they have not ordered them at all, in which case the order will be

00:11:37.719 --> 00:11:41.640
the alphabetical order of the neighborhood, we're going to give them another message.

00:11:41.640 --> 00:11:46.599
And you can imagine stringing along as many of these as you think are relevant for the exercises

00:11:46.599 --> 00:11:51.479
you develop. And then probably you want to write a catch-all statement that's like, not quite,

00:11:51.479 --> 00:11:56.039
take a peek at the hints. If the students are making mistakes that you can't even anticipate

00:11:56.039 --> 00:12:01.239
when you write the tests, you can kind of leave the hints to take care of that.

00:12:01.239 --> 00:12:06.200
And if you use these tutorials over multiple semesters or multiple workshops, multiple

00:12:06.200 --> 00:12:11.400
learning or teaching engagements, you're probably going to learn about the various mistakes students

00:12:11.400 --> 00:12:18.200
make based on their questions. And then you might iteratively build these tests to capture more

00:12:18.200 --> 00:12:25.719
mistakes that they might make. So we've talked about writing these exercises. What about collecting

00:12:25.719 --> 00:12:32.119
data? LearnR and GradeThis alone don't have some facility to allow you to collect data from

00:12:32.119 --> 00:12:37.719
students. Specifically, the LearnR package makes this possible, but it doesn't itself offer the

00:12:37.719 --> 00:12:43.479
functionality to do so. So for that, I use a different package called LearnRHash, which hashes

00:12:43.479 --> 00:12:49.719
the student results and then allows you as the instructor to decode them. So a setting where I

00:12:49.719 --> 00:12:56.359
might use this is probably similar to this, where I give them a coding exercise first. It says make

00:12:56.359 --> 00:13:04.359
a histogram of the prices. So let's go ahead and actually do that. The data set is adbnb.

00:13:04.359 --> 00:13:09.559
The variable is price. We're going to have them make a histogram.

00:13:12.760 --> 00:13:27.320
And here are the labels x, y, and title. Maybe something like this. They go ahead and run their

00:13:27.320 --> 00:13:33.880
code and they get some warnings and submit their answer. It says you got it right. And note that

00:13:33.880 --> 00:13:38.440
there are a couple of warnings. We'll get to those in a little bit because here our focus is a little

00:13:38.440 --> 00:13:44.599
bit different. So we follow this on with some multiple choice questions. Which of the following

00:13:44.599 --> 00:13:50.599
describes the shape of the distribution? It's right skewed and unimodal. And let's go ahead

00:13:50.599 --> 00:13:56.919
and pick another answer for the second question. This one happens to be incorrect. Okay, so when it

00:13:56.919 --> 00:14:02.760
comes time to submitting their answers with the LearnRHash package, students can generate a hash,

00:14:02.760 --> 00:14:06.840
which is going to look very cryptic to them, which is exactly what it's meant to do.

00:14:06.840 --> 00:14:12.520
They can select it and copy it. And then I like embedding directly into the LearnR tutorial

00:14:12.520 --> 00:14:19.080
something like a Google form or another form your institution might use, where the students can

00:14:19.080 --> 00:14:25.799
submit their information. If you're using something that directly your university uses, for example,

00:14:25.799 --> 00:14:31.080
this form could ask them to authenticate first. If you want to make sure that who is

00:14:31.080 --> 00:14:38.520
answering the questions is actually who you think it is. And you can ask them to paste their hash

00:14:38.520 --> 00:14:44.919
that they generated here. And I also like using this form to collect some free form information

00:14:44.919 --> 00:14:51.080
from the students as well. So a question phrased as, write about one or two questions you didn't

00:14:51.080 --> 00:14:56.440
get right initially, but were able to solve after a few tries. What was difficult about them? What

00:14:56.440 --> 00:15:02.039
did you ultimately learn? And let the students write some free form answers and submit their

00:15:02.039 --> 00:15:09.239
results. On your end, what you're going to see is this hash that the students have submitted.

00:15:09.239 --> 00:15:14.840
And you'll be able to decode that and be able to take a look at their multiple choice questions

00:15:14.840 --> 00:15:20.359
and the answers they gave for those. And the exercises, that's the coding exercises,

00:15:20.359 --> 00:15:26.119
and the answers they gave for those as well. For summative feedback for grading, I usually tend to

00:15:26.359 --> 00:15:29.640
mark the multiple choice questions, but you could choose to do both.

00:15:30.919 --> 00:15:37.000
These data are collected in a Google spreadsheet, so you can view the Google spreadsheet itself.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:42.679
I've pre-populated it with some mock student data. And what you can do is using the Google

00:15:42.679 --> 00:15:49.159
Sheets 4 package, get that data and calculate the students' scores by matching their answers to

00:15:49.159 --> 00:15:54.119
a key. And then also take a look at the free form answers. I like taking a look at bigrams,

00:15:54.119 --> 00:15:59.719
for example, to see what are some concepts that were mentioned many times as being difficult for

00:15:59.719 --> 00:16:05.239
the students, so you might tailor your next lesson accordingly. Lastly, let's talk about

00:16:05.239 --> 00:16:11.799
distributing these at scale. One option, obviously, is to deploy these to something like ShinyAppsIO

00:16:11.799 --> 00:16:17.799
or another Shiny server from the RStudio IDE with push button deploy, just clicking on publish.

00:16:17.799 --> 00:16:22.599
It works out of the box. It's great. But something you might want to be careful about is that if you

00:16:22.599 --> 00:16:28.599
have a large class and a strict deadline, many students might try to access the tutorial at the

00:16:28.599 --> 00:16:33.640
same time. So you've got to make sure that the parameters for your deployment are set up properly

00:16:33.640 --> 00:16:38.599
in order to be able to handle that. You might want to give it more memory. You might want to

00:16:39.400 --> 00:16:44.679
create more instances. And at some point, if you have a really large course and you expect students

00:16:44.679 --> 00:16:49.719
to be doing things at the same time, you may need to think about using one of the paid tiers of

00:16:49.719 --> 00:16:55.799
ShinyAppsIO, and that may or may not be feasible for your setting. So another option is to distribute

00:16:55.799 --> 00:17:01.239
them within a package. Here I'm going to give an example from the dsbox package, which accompanies

00:17:01.239 --> 00:17:06.760
the data science course in a box curriculum. And yes, I am saying that you can make an R package,

00:17:06.760 --> 00:17:12.599
and you might be new to doing that, so you can use this as a skeleton for doing so. But the nice thing

00:17:12.599 --> 00:17:20.119
is really what you want to focus on is that the tutorials go in the inst folder in a subfolder

00:17:20.119 --> 00:17:26.280
called tutorials of the package. Inside that is a single folder for each one of the tutorials. This

00:17:26.280 --> 00:17:31.479
package happens to have eight of them, and inside that is the R markdown file where you developed

00:17:31.479 --> 00:17:38.040
your tutorial and any accompanying files that go along with it. Chances are you may not want to put

00:17:38.040 --> 00:17:43.719
this tutorial on CRAN, maybe it's not for wide distribution, but you can ask your students to

00:17:43.719 --> 00:17:49.560
install it directly from GitHub, or if you're using something like RStudio Cloud, you can ask them to,

00:17:49.560 --> 00:17:55.239
you can pre-install it for them. And within the RStudio IDE, they will be ready to be launched

00:17:55.239 --> 00:18:01.319
soon as the students start that RStudio session. I usually tell my students once you launch the

00:18:01.319 --> 00:18:07.079
tutorial, just make that tutorial pane, maximize it, and it looks just like they're interacting

00:18:07.079 --> 00:18:13.239
with it within the web browser. But now you're not relying on a service like ShinyApps.io to be

00:18:13.239 --> 00:18:18.680
hosting your tutorial, so it really doesn't matter how many students are using it at the same time,

00:18:18.680 --> 00:18:24.520
as long as your RStudio session allows that. The barrier to entry for getting started with

00:18:24.520 --> 00:18:30.040
LearnR is pretty low, especially if you're already an R markdown user. In fact, the tutorials in the

00:18:30.040 --> 00:18:35.719
dsbox package were co-developed with students with only one semester of introductory data science

00:18:35.719 --> 00:18:40.920
under their belt, so when I say it has a low entry point, I really mean it. We all know that

00:18:40.920 --> 00:18:46.839
students get better at coding or whatever they're learning with practice. We also probably mostly

00:18:46.839 --> 00:18:52.520
agree that formative feedback that nudges learners in the right direction while they're working on

00:18:52.520 --> 00:18:57.719
the exercises, as opposed to summative feedback that comes weeks after they're done, can have

00:18:57.719 --> 00:19:03.719
positive effects on their learning and enjoyment. Plus, providing individual feedback to students,

00:19:03.719 --> 00:19:10.520
especially for exercises narrow in scope, can turn into dreadful busy work for us educators.

00:19:10.520 --> 00:19:16.839
So while developing meaningful automated feedback can be quite tedious and time-consuming, I think

00:19:16.839 --> 00:19:22.760
that's a much more intellectually engaging way to spend your time as an instructor. It's also a

00:19:22.760 --> 00:19:27.719
great opportunity to develop software engineering skills, like writing robust tests, bringing

00:19:27.719 --> 00:19:33.160
together your pedagogical and technical expertise. You can find materials for this talk, including

00:19:33.160 --> 00:19:38.439
the source code for the LearnR tutorial we worked through, and links to resources to learn more at

00:19:38.439 --> 00:19:46.280
rstd.io slash global 2021 slash mcr. Thank you for watching! And remember that comment from your

00:19:46.280 --> 00:19:51.959
chair about no more TA support? With what LearnR, GreatThis, and LearnR Hash can offer, you might get

00:19:51.959 --> 00:19:54.760
closer to responding. Bring it on!

